"Dejean A., M. Carpenter J., Gibernau M., Leponce M., Corbara B.","Nest relocation and high mortality rate in a Neotropical social wasp: Impact of an exceptionally rainy La Niña year",2010,"Comptes Rendus - Biologies","333","1",,"35","40",,,10.1016/j.crvi.2009.10.007,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77049088909&partnerID=40&md5=93fc46a7ae95cf49bf3643ab0505ef48","CNRS - UMR 8172, Ecofog, écologie des forêts de Guyane, BP 709, 97387 Kourou cedex, France; Division of Invertebrate Zoology, American Museum of Natural History, Central Park West at, 79th Street, NY 10024, United States; Biological Evaluation Section, Royal Belgian Institute of Natural Sciences, 29, rue Vautier, 1000 Brussels, Belgium; CNRS, UMR 6023, laboratoire microorganismes génome et environnement (LMGE), 63177 Aubière, France; LMGE, Clermont université, université Blaise-Pascal, BP 10448, 63000 Clermont-Ferrand, France","Dejean, A., CNRS - UMR 8172, Ecofog, écologie des forêts de Guyane, BP 709, 97387 Kourou cedex, France; M. Carpenter, J., Division of Invertebrate Zoology, American Museum of Natural History, Central Park West at, 79th Street, NY 10024, United States; Gibernau, M., CNRS - UMR 8172, Ecofog, écologie des forêts de Guyane, BP 709, 97387 Kourou cedex, France; Leponce, M., Biological Evaluation Section, Royal Belgian Institute of Natural Sciences, 29, rue Vautier, 1000 Brussels, Belgium; Corbara, B., CNRS, UMR 6023, laboratoire microorganismes génome et environnement (LMGE), 63177 Aubière, France, LMGE, Clermont université, université Blaise-Pascal, BP 10448, 63000 Clermont-Ferrand, France","After noting the forecast of a La Niña episode, associated with heavy rainfall in French Guiana, we monitored the fate of wasp nests before and during the 2006 short rainy season. The population of the most abundant epiponine wasp species, Polybia bistriata, decreased dramatically during the short rainy season (60.6% of the nests disappeared) then remained low for at least 18 months. Colonies that survived moved from the shelter of large, low leaves (a situation well adapted to the previous dry season) of the most frequent substrate tree, Clusia grandiflora (Clusiaceae), to upper leaves, better ventilated and whose orientation provides good protection from the rain. Therefore, the possibility of moving the nest higher during the first rains following the dry season seems very adaptive as colonies that do not do so are eliminated during the La Niña years, whose frequency will increase with global climate change. © 2009 Académie des sciences.","French Guiana; La Niña; Microevolution; Population size variation; Vespidae","climate change; environmental effect; La Nina; mortality; population decline; population size; survival; wasp; adaptive behavior; arthropod community; article; climate change; Clusia; Clusia grandiflora; controlled study; El Nino; meteorological phenomena; nesting; nonhuman; Polybia bistriata; seasonal variation; species translocation; temperature acclimatization; wasp; Adaptation, Biological; Animals; Behavior, Animal; Climate; Clusia; French Guiana; Nesting Behavior; Plant Leaves; Rain; Seasons; Tropical Climate; Wasps; French Guiana; Clusia grandiflora; Clusiaceae; Polybia; Vespidae",,,,,,"Visscher, P.K., Group decision making in nest-site selection among social insects (2007) An. Rev. Entomol., 52, pp. 255-275; Jeanne, R.L., The swarm-founding Polistinae (1991) The social biology of wasps, pp. 191-231. , Ross K.G., and Matthews R.W. (Eds), Cornell University Press, New York; Dejean, A., Corbara, B., Carpenter, J.M., Nesting site selection by wasps in the Guianese rain forest (1998) Ins. Soc., 45, pp. 33-41; Corbara, B., Carpenter, J.M., Céréghino, R., Leponce, M., Gibernau, M., Dejean, A., Diversity and nest site selection of social wasps along Guianese forest edges: assessing the influence of arboreal ants (2009) C. R. Biol., 332, pp. 470-479; Hunt, J.H., Carpenter, J.M., Intra-specific nest form variation in some Neotropica